{{Infobox power station | name = Blyth Harbour Wind Farm | image = | image_caption = | location_map = Northumberland | coordinates = {{coord|55.1222|-1.49027|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | name_official = | country = [[England]], [[United Kingdom]] | location = The Port of [[Blyth, Northumberland]] | status = Operational | construction_began = | commissioned = January 1993 | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = [[Hainsford Developments (Blyth Harbour) Limited]] | operator = | ps_units_operational = 9 × 0.3 MW | ps_units_manu_model = WindMaster | wind_hub_height = | wind_rotor_diameter = | wind_rated_speed = | wind_farm_type = | wind_site_elevation = 5 ft | wind_site_usage = | wind_offshore_depth = | wind_offshore_distance = | ps_electrical_capacity = 2.7&nbsp;MW | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | website = }}
'''Blyth Harbour Wind Farm''' is a coastal wind farm located along the East Pier of the Port of [[Blyth, Northumberland|Blyth]]. Commissioned in January 1993 it consists of nine 0.3[[Megawatt|MW]] WindMaster [[Wind turbine|turbines]] giving a total capacity of 2.7MW. It was developed by [[AMEC]] Wind and is owned by Hainsford Developments (Blyth Harbour) Limited.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bwea.com/ukwed/operational.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-12-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102132011/http://www.bwea.com/ukwed/operational.asp |archivedate=2012-11-02 |df= }}</ref>
==Repowering==
In January 2008 consent was granted to replace the existing nine turbines with seven new ones. Six of these would generate 2.5MW each, and a seventh larger one would produce 7.58MW (if it is an [[Enercon E-126]])and be the largest land-based turbine in Europe at {{convert|163|m|abbr=on}} tall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-news/2008/07/17/giant-wind-turbine-is-set-for-go-ahead-61634-21355057/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-11-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307113103/http://www.journallive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-news/2008/07/17/giant-wind-turbine-is-set-for-go-ahead-61634-21355057/ |archivedate=2012-03-07 |df= }}</ref>
As of September 2012, the first new turbine became operational, producing up to 3.4 MW of power (more than the original nine turbines combined). The turbine is a REpower 3.4M104, with a 76m hub height.
